ew to found the monastic communities of Meteora. The meteors are gigantic rocks, dark stalagmites rising to the sky. The monasteries with their  wooden galleries, and projecting roofs crown the rocky peaks. They contain relics, art objects, rare manuscripts. They are decorated with frescoes, gilded wood and precious icons. A wonder to the visitor. \r\nAfter our visit to the Meteors we make our way for the very picturesque village of palaios Panteleiomonas, where we will have the chance to stroll around, enjoy the amazing view, and taste the local cuisine. We overnight in the amazing village of Litochoro, at the foot of Mount Olympus, home to the 12 Goods of the antiquity.\r\n\r\n<span class="number">05</span> Fifth day St. Athanasios Monasterie – Vergina - Kavala\r\n\r\nAfter breakfast, we make our way on the mountain in order to visit the monasteries of Agios Athanasios, amazing frescoes and architecture write in the middle of virgin nature.\r\nWe continue to Vergina. The Royal Tombs of Vergina, Tomb of Philip II of Macedonia, father of Alexander the Great. Just an hour away from Thessaloniki we offer you the visit of an exceptional archaeological site located in Vergina. It is here that Aigai was discovered in the nineteenth century, the first ancient capital of the kingdom of Macedonia. The most important remains are the monumental palace, lavishly decorated with mosaics and painted stucco, and the burial ground with more than three hundred burial mounds, some dating back to the eleventh century BC. Among the royal tombs in the Great Tumulus is included that of Philip II. He conquered all the Greek cities, paving the way for his son Alexander and for the expansion of the Hellenistic world. This exceptional archaeological discovery is proposed to the visitor in an equally exceptional setting. Vergina is an outstanding example of a significant milestone in the history of Western civilization, the passage of the city-state of classical times to the imperial organiza